Frank P. Pellegrino



        Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_P._PellegrinoUpdated: 2017-06-25T20:03Z
      
For other people with the same name, see Frank Pellegrino.Frank Paul PellegrinoExecutive Photo, International Hat Co., 1942Born(1901-04-10)April 10, 1901Cerisano in Calabria, ItalyDiedMay 22, 1975(1975-05-22) (aged 74)St. Louis, MissouriOccupationFormer Chairman and CEO of International Hat CompanyFounder of George Tilles, Jr. ParkFounder of Maria Pellegrino ParkSpouse(s)Ida KroppChildrenFrank G. Pellegrino, Sr. (1923-2007)Parent(s)Ferdinando PellegrinoMaria PellegrinoRelativesJosephine Pellegrino (sister)Sarah Pellegrino (sister)Carmen Pellegrino (sister)Lawrence Pellegrino (brother)Christine Pellegrino (sister)Rose Pellegrino (sister)Mary Pellegrino (sister)Frank Paul Pellegrino (April 10, 1901 – May 22, 1975) was an American businessman and philanthropist.[1] He was the longest-serving Chairman and CEO of the International Hat Company.[2] Pellegrino built numerous factories across Southeastern Missouri, managing the company into becoming the largest manufacturing employer in the region by the 1960s.[3]Pellegrino also engaged in numerous philanthropic projects throughout his life. Most notably, he established and funded municipal parks in Southeastern Missouri. His donations resulted in the founding of both George Tilles, Jr. Park and Maria Pellegrino Park.[4][5]Contents1 Early life2 Career3 Philanthropy4 See also5 References6 Bibliography7 External linksEarly lifePellegrino was the third of eight children and the only child not born in St. Louis. His father and mother emigrated from Italy in 1891 from Cerisano in Calabria, Italy. His father, Ferdinando Pellegrino, was a soldier in the Royal Italian Army in the late 19th century. He received American citizenship in 1896 after renouncing fealty to King Umberto I of Italy. With the death of Ferdinando's father in 1900, the family returned to Italy to sell the Cerisano farm. At this time, Italy was in the midst of a depression. While waiting the sale of the property, Pellegrino was born in 1901. It took several years to sell the property before the family permanently returned to the United States.As a teenager, Pellegrino began working for the International Hat Company in 1920, as a hat rack assembly lineman.[2] Several years later, his sister Sarah and Josephine would join him as seamstresses for the company.[6] At the age of 19, he married Ida Kropp, a fellow employee and German immigrant that worked as a seamstress at the plant.CareerMain article: International Hat CompanyBy the 1930s, Pellegrino served as Vice President of International Hat under George Tilles, Jr., the nephew of horse racing magnate Cap Tilles.[2][7] During World War II, Pellegrino became Chairman and CEO, serving until his death in 1975. He was a driving force for the production of military pith helmets for the United States Army, Navy, and Marines during World War II. Under his management, the company expanded to incorporate factories, warehouses, and sales offices throughout Missouri, Texas, New York, and Mexico.[8]PhilanthropyIn 1962, Pellegrino donated land and money to establish the first municipal park in the history of Oran, Missouri.[4] The park was dedicated as the George Tilles, Jr. Park in honor of Pellegrino's business associate and close friend.[4] The site of Oran was chosen due to the International Hat factory Tilles and Pellegrino built there together. As a condition for founding the park, Pellegrino petitioned the city that future funding of the new recreational facilities and park upkeep be managed through municipal taxation. The measure was placed on the voting ballot and passed with 93 percent of voters approving.[4] In 1969, Pellegrino donated land to Marble Hill, Missouri to form a new municipal park.[5][9] Maria Pellegrino Park was named in honor of his mother.[10] The site was officially dedicated by the Director of Missouri State Parks Joseph Jaegar, Marble Hill Mayor Leon Sander, and Lutesville Mayor Orvile Liley.[9][11] At the park dedication ceremony, the local officials formally declared the event as "Pellegrino Appreciation Day".[9][12] In 1972, the Missouri State House of Representatives passed a special motion to honor Pellegrino's lifetime of philanthropy towards improving the state.[9] On behalf of the State House, a special award was also presented to him.[9]See alsoBiography portalMaria Pellegrino ParkTilles Memorial City ParkInternational Hat CompanyList of People from St. LouisList of Italian-American Business PeopleReferences^ "Frank P. Pellegrino". Find a Grave. Retrieved March 23, 2016. ^ a b c International Hat Company 1942, p. 6.^ Schmidt 1990, p. 81.^ a b c d The Missourian. "$10,000 Gift, Voter Approval Bring City Park". The Southeast Missourian, Cape Girardeau, April 2, 1962. Retrieved on 8 January 2014.^ a b "Twin Cities Get Offer of Land, Cash for Park". The Southeast Missourian, Cape Girardeau, April 2, 1969. Retrieved on 8 January 2014.^ International Hat Company 1942, p. 9.^ Carver 2002, p. 248.^ Schmidt 1990, p. 79.^ a b c d e The Missourian. "Dedicate New Park at Ceremonies Sunday", The Southeast Missourian, Cape Girardeau, June 2, 1972. Retrieved on 25 November 2013.^ "Cites Need for More Park Facilities". Southeastern Missourian. June 5, 1972. Retrieved 26 September 2016. ^ The Missourian. "Park Benefactor" The Southeast Missourian, Cape Girardeau, June 5, 1972. Retrieved on 8 January 2014.^ The Missourian. "Dedicate New Bollinger Park". The Southeast Missourian, Cape Girardeau, June 5, 1972. Retrieved on 8 January 2014.BibliographyCarver, Nancy Ellen. Talk with Tilles: Selling Life in Fort Smith, Arkansas. St. Louis: Xlibris Publishing, October 21, 2002. ISBN 1401071996International Hat Company. International Harvest Hat Company: A Brief History, 1917-1942 25th Anniversary Edition, St. Louis: International Hat Company, 1942.Schmidt, Richard John. The Divestiture Option: A Guide for Financial and Corporate Planning Executives, Greenwood Publishing Group, Jan 1, 1990. ISBN 0899303978External linksWikimedia Commons has media related to Frank Pellegrino.Pellegrino Park, City of Marble HillvteInternational Hat CompanyKey peopleIsaac AppleGeorge Tilles, Sr.George Tilles, Jr.Frank P. PellegrinoFrank G. PellegrinoProductsAmerican fiber helmetM1 helmetFiber linerBusiness entitiesGeneral Fibre CompanyMarble Hill Hat CompanyLand DonationsGeorge Tilles Jr. Memorial ParkPellegrino ParkFacilitiesSoulard WarehouseFactory LocationsSt. LouisOranPiedmontMarble HillDexterChaffee






